title: Preston Presbyterian Community Church
creator: Preston Citizen
description: Newspaper Article, "Home Wrecker," Preston Citizen, April 8, 2009.  Picture and caption of demolition of first Presbyterian church building.  Caption:  The large white building on the corner of First West and Oneida, first built as the first Presbyterian Church in Preston, was gutted and leveld Friday.  Built at the turn of the century, it was purchased by the Greaves family in 1914, reported the Daughters of Utah Pioneers in "The Trail Blazer."  The white house just south of the church on the same property was reported to be the rectory, where the minister lived.

title: First Security Bank Building, Preston, Idaho
creator: Unknown
description: The First Security Bank Building was on the northwest corner of the main intersection (Oneida and State Streets).  It was originally the First National Bank, which was merged with First Security in 1931.  A year later the interior was modernized and in 1940 the exterior was smoothed over and stuccoed a monolithic white.  Quarters were built upstairs for the Elks Lodge.  Professional offices were also upstairs.  Heavy fire damaged the building in 1948.  It was torn down and a new bank built in 1970.
subject: Preston Businesses; Banks
source: The Hometown Sketchbook, by Newell Hart.  Neil Nelson, Douglas Webb, and Ray Cutler
source_legacy: Digitized version of an old photograph.

title: Military Parade, Preston, Idaho, 1943
creator: Base Photographic Service, Hill Field, Ogden, Utah
description: In 1943, in connection with a military parade and concert, a bond drive was under way to earn money for the war.  On the corner of First Security Bank was a quota board with the following numbers:  Franklin Co. Quota Board, E Bond Quota, as follows:  $275,000.  ARMY, $31,900; Weston, $11,000; Dayton, $8,800, Clifton, $7,700, Linrose, $4,400.  AIR CORPS, $37,950, Franklin, $14,300, Fairview, $13,200, Whitney, $6,600, Mapleton, $5,850.  NAVY,  $31,35.  Mink Creek, $7,700, Riverdale, $6,600, Treasureton, $5,500, Glenco, $3,300, Winder, $3,300, Banida, $2,700, Glendale, $2,200.  MARINES, $76,450.  Preston 1st Ward, $24,200, Preston 4th Ward, $17,600, Preston 3rd Ward, $16,500, Preston 2nd Ward, $8,800, Preston 6th Ward, $4,950, Preston 5th Ward, $4,400.  Have you bought your E bond today?

title: Central Market, Preston, Idaho
creator: Unknown
description: The Central Market picture is backwards, according to Newell Hart's book, Hometown Sketches.  The Grand Theatre marquee should be on the left of the picture.  Don Greaves owned the IGA store, which also housed Rust Pastry Shop and Purser Meat Market, which was in back of the store.  Central Market was between Oneida and 100 South on the west side of the street.  At the time of this photo, Preston had a population of 4500 people, as indicated on the store front.
subject: Preston Businesses
source: Neil Nelson, Douglas Webb. Hometown Sketchbook, by Newell Hart

title: Rotary Club, Preston, Idaho, 1937
creator: Unknown
description: Photo was taken on January 20, 1937.  Left table, clockwise, beginning with man in center with napkin in lap:  M. O. Merrill, Eugene Worley, Alan Carlson, (two behind) Paul Winn and Theo Petterborg, Ben Johnson, Angus Condie, David E. Davis, (woman behind _____), Mrs. Beckstead, Louis Thomas (barely visible), E. A. Crockett, M. Willis Hendricks.  Table on right, beginning at left, clockwise:  Calvin Foss, Dave L. McClun, R. F. Campbell, Dr. G. W. States, Allen R. Cutler, Harley Greaves, Dr. S. P. Packer, James A. Bullock, T. R. Bowden, Nephi Larson, Wm. J. Fryer, Ray C. Bright, Clifford Warr, William Paul Merrill, and William D. Davis.  Standing in the back, left to right:  Erwin Roswell Spilsbury, Mr. Robertts, guest; Wm. P. Shumway, Secretary; Helen Palmer, Pianist; Geo. Paull, Board Member; Geo. Burgi, President of Club; Smith Allen, Board Member; J. Homer Johnson; Dr. Samuel S. Evans, Board Member; Dr. S. E. Nelson, Board Member.  The picture was taken in the Elks' Club Rooms above First Security Bank.
subject: Rotary Club; Preston People

title: Pioneer Ferry and Bridge
creator: Myrna Fuller
description: DUP Monument No. 236.  The plaque reads:  concrete shaft located 1/2 mile west on Bear River marks the site of the Nathan Williams Packer Toll Ferry and Bridge, one of the first on the river.  The ferry operated with rope and carried equivalent of one team and wagon.   In 1869 a bridge was built for use of mail and stage coaches en route to Montana mines, but was washed out.   Rebuilt of cribs and log piling.   Again destroyed by high waters.   Across the river is the site of Bridge Port, an overland station consisting of dugouts and log cabins.

title: Battle of Bear River Monument Plaque, Preston, Idaho
creator: Myrna Fuller
description: No. 16.  Erected 1863.  The Battle of Bear River was fought in this vicinity January 29, 1863.  Col. P. E. Conner, leading 300 California volunteers from Camp Douglas, Utah, against Bannock and Shoshoni Indians, guilty of hostile attacks on emigrants and settlers, engaged about 500 Indians of whom 200-300 were killed, or incapacitated, including about 90 combatant women and children.   14 soldiers were killed, 4 officers and 49 men were wounded, of whom 1 officer and 7 men died later.  79 were severely frozen.  Chiefs Bear Hunter, Sagwitch, and Lehi were reported killed.  175 horses and much stolen property were recovered.  70 lodges were burned.
subject: Historic Markers in Franklin County; Bear River Massacre

title: Pioneer Women Plaque on Bear River Massacre Monument, Preston, Idaho
creator: Myrna Fuller
description: Bear River Massacre Monument Plaque.  No. 186, Daughters of Utah Pioneers, Franklin County.  The plaque reads:  Attacks by the Indians on the peaceful inhabitants of this vicinity led to the final battle here January 29, 1863.  The conflict occurred in deep snow and bitter cold.  Scores of wounded and frozen soldiers were taken from the battlefield to the Latter-day Saint community of Franklin.   Here pioneer women trained through trials and necessity of frontier living accepted the responsibility of caring for the wounded until they could be removed to Camp Douglas, Utah.  Two Indian women and three children, found alive after the encounter, were given homes in Franklin.
subject: Historic Markers in Franklin County; Bear River Massacre

title: Bear River Massacre Sign, Preston, Idaho
creator: Myrna Fuller
description: Bear River Massacre Sign on the massacre site, north and west of Preston on Highway 91.  The sign reads:  Very few Northwestern Shoshoni Indians survived a battle here that turned into a massacre by Col. P. E. Connor's California Volunteers.   In 1863, Connor and his force set out from Salt Lake on a cold January campaign in response to friction between Indians and white travelers.   They found more than 400 Shoshoni settled in a winter camp on Battle Creek.   When Connor struck at daybreak on January 29, the Shoshoni suffered a massacre unrivaled in American history.
subject: Historic Markers in Franklin County; Bear River Massacre

title: Utah and Northern Railway Sign, Preston, Idaho
creator: Myrna Fuller
description: The Utah and Northern Railway Sign, No. 257 is on the Bear River Massacre Site, north and west of Preston on Highway 91.  The sign reads:  One mile south and directly west of this highway, an old 1978 railway grade still is visible although trains have not used it since 1890.  Jay Gould--a nationally prominent financier and Union Pacific owenr--extended Utah and Northern service north from Franklin to Montana by 1880.  A narrow gauge line until 1887, it helped build up Cache Valley and accounted for many new Idaho cities and towns farther north.  But small, wood-burning locomotives had a hard time ascending this hill.   After a more direct route 4 miles west of here was completed, service north of Preston was abandoned on this grade.

title: Oxford, Idaho School Bell
creator: James Dee Boyce
description: When the Oxford School House was remodeled and the bell tower removed, the bell was sold to Janette and Wilford Bosworth for $3.50.  They had to take it down with a series of blocks and tackle.  The rope pulley was removed and Floyd Helmandollar built and mounted it on a wooden frame.   The Bosworths had the bell at their home in Treasureton until they moved to Winder.  In 1993, Dee Boyce, Janette's brother, acquired the bell and had it refurbished and mounted on a new wooden frame.

title: Oxford, Idaho Croshaw Reunion
creator: Seattle Times
description: Picture is from the Seattle Times, Monday, July 11, 1955.  The William E. Croshaws and John J. Croshaws and their families got together for a picnic at Lake Forest Park yesterday.  Counting the descendants and in-laws, 108 attended.  In this photograph, Mr. and Mrs. William Croshaw, 807 E. 200th St., and their branch of the family were at the left.  Mr. and Mrs. John J. Croshaw of Logan, Utah and their descendants were at the right.  William and John Croshaw are cousins.  Their wives are sisters.  Both are retired farmers.  The William Croshaws have 11 children, 26 grandchildren and 15 great-grand- children.  They have been married 58 years.  The John Croshaws have 12 children, 37 grandchildren and 16 great-grand- children.  They have been married 56 years.  A reunion was held in Utah last year.  [Both Croshaw families had their beginnings in Oxford, Idaho]

title: Oxford, Idaho; Mines
creator: James Dee Boyce
description: Lucky Baker Mining and Development Co. Inc. stock certificate, made out to James Jensen for 2,000 shares.  November 3, 1938.  Signed by armin A. Rosenbau and Alex McLachlan.  Shares were 10 cents each.  This certificate was given to Bob James Jensen for cooking for the mine crew.  James gave the stock certificate and picture to Dee Boyce in 1983 during an interview.  The mine was a failure.  The little smelter built just south of the Hill home only smelted out one batch of ore.  On the second attempt their generator quit and the ore solidified in the crucible.  Many area people provided work and supplies for the mining operation and were given Stock Certificates for pay, which proved worthless.

title: Oxford, Idaho; Historical Marker
creator: James Dee Boyce
description: Daughters of Utah Pioneers No. 55; Erected December, 1939.  Settlement of Oxford - July, 1864, a company of explorers were sent to Idaho by President Brigham Young to locate suitable places for settlements.  The same year NoahBrimhall and John Boice built the first homes in Oxford.  William G. Nelson, George D. Lake, and George T. Black were presiding elders until 1876 when William F. fisher became the first bishop.  Mr Fisher, noted express rider, erected this building 1876 for his law and mercantile busines.  Oxford, one of the first settlements, was for years the main trading center north of Cache Valley.  Bannock County Company
subject: Historical Monument Plaque; Daughters of Utah Pioneers

creator: James Dee Boyce
description: Dee Boyce in the crevice on Oxford Peak. title: Rexall Corner, Preston, Idaho
creator: Unknown
description: Postcard Picture of Rexall Corner, as it was known for yeras.  Riter Drug was built in 1900-01.  The Bell Telephone switchboard was upstairs and the town curfew/fire siren was mounted on top; when the strolling cop was needed a red light shone from the corner, activated by Central.  The drugstore was the town's nerve center, even the phone number was "one."  Looking down East Oneida from State Street.  Smith and Sons Produce. 1-17-11.  Back of postcard:  Foss Drug, or Bayles Drug on corner, Uncle Kay's store on right.   Addressed to Parley L. Carver, Box 426, Newport News, VA.  44 years ago the advent of your Pa.   We are all well a little snow.   Walt Carver is called on a mission.  He never called here for Ex mass(?)  I have been doing some wash on county Road of late. _____of the people are better now though Dave Evans little boy is quite sick.  Haven't heard from Plain City for some time.  With best wishes to you we received the letter from the coast.  Mom
subject: Preston Businesses

title: Preston Main Street, Preston, Idaho
creator: Ewing Photography
description: Postcard photograph of Preston Main Street (west side) looking south from Oneida Street, dated 12-14-1910.  Businesses shown:  John Larsen and Sons (men who officed upstairs - S. C. Chadwick, Ezra F. Woolley, P. M. condie, P. J. Evans, A. H. Jensen, H. B. Sternberg (state engineer); Foss Brothers Dry Goods Store (1905),Pioneer Meat Market (1903, Rogers and Hawkes), later Palace Meat Market; Foss Drug (Co-op Drug), 1905.   Back of postcard:  All at home except one.   Santa is expected soon.   Trust that he will find the absent one.   He has a present for each.   John is pleased to bee Home.  Sister and Duward is trying hard to keep awake.   No snow.  All is well.  With best wishes from home.  Addressed to Elder Parley L. Carver, Newport News, VA.

title: Farmer's Equity Building, Preston, Idaho, 1915
creator: Unknown
description: Farmers Equity building was around as early as 1903.  Used to be a livery stable, thus the wide door. title: Ezra Smart Foss and The three Foss stores with remodeled fronts.
creator: Newell Hart
description: Ezra Smart Foss and The three Foss stores with remodeled fronts. After grandfather Foss died, Uncle Ez remodeled the front of the drug-store and named it the Foss Drug. There were a lot of ceramic tiles left over from the store front and pavement which were given to me and my brother (Bob and Van Hansen). We played with them in various ways for a long time. Mother's cousin (Connie Foss Gibbons) remodeled the Foss Clothing Store front and lived above that store. Ez and LaRene Foss lived above the drug-store for a few years after their son Carter Foss was born.

title: The Foss Furniture Store.
creator: Newell Hart
description: Foss Furniture Store, Preston, Idaho. We kids used to like to swing around on the pipes holding up this metal awning. About ten years later my brother Van and I used to load our newspapers on our bicycles here to begin our delivery routes.

title: Part of Main Street in Preston, Idaho
creator: Newell Hart
description: Part of Main Street in Preston, Idaho. As kids, we would go to the movies at the "Grand" or the "Islis" Theater every Saturday afternoon; but first we had to take our pennies into the "Candy Kitchen" next door and spend half an hour picking out what items we wanted which were displayed in the window. (Jaw-breakers, All-day suckers, Licorice twists, carmels, "Nigger-babies", or dark-secrets - all satisfied our hunger for sweets.)

title: Construction of Preston High School's first football field
creator: Unknown
description: Ern Porter's WPA crew building Preston High's first football stadium, now known as Cutler Field.  This swail had been the expansive Frog   Pond the school  kids played in.     Many sections of drain tile to be used are evident in the scene.  Prior to this project the football games were played in the ball park, or rodeo arena as it is now claled.  Looking northerly toward the old Wilf Smith home, 129 East, 100 South.  Among the workmen are Leonard Hansen, Jim Corbridge and Ray Merrill.  Ern Porter recalls:  "The money was handled by an organization under the county commissioners.  Wilford Smith was the first county foreman appointed by the commissioners and I was the first appointee under him.  The stadium was our first project--and then the airport.
